column38: In my opinion, the typical undocumented immigrant has come to the US in search of a better life, and is willing to work as hard as any native-born Americans to get it. Coming in without proper documentation does not automatically make someone a "criminal" anymore than jaywalking does. Undocumented immigrants generally commit fewer crimes than people born in the US (perhaps due to fear of unjust deportation for even the smallest crime), which is why it's inaccurate to say undocumented immigrants are criminals. However, at the individual level, I try to avoid generalizing-- I would say that your average undocumented immigrant is, in most ways, very similar to your typical documented immigrant or US-born person, and deserves to be judged on his or her merits, values, and contributions, not on immigration status or country of origin.

column38: From my experience, most undocumented immigrants are from Mexico. Most of these people came to America to seek a better life for themselves and their families. My mother is an immigrant from the Philippines who was hoping for the same thing. She entered legally and is now a naturalized citizen, but I know the process to immigrate into the United States is extremely tough and is simply not an option for everyone. My aunt applied for a green card and it was not granted for 12 years, by which point she had almost forgotten that she had applied. I think immigrants are just people who want the best for their families, and that makes them no different than any natural-born citizen. Even if they entered illegally, they are no different because no human being is illegal.
